Since $V$ and $W$ are midpoints, $VW$ is half the length of $RS,$ and $UV$ is half the length of $PQ.$  Since $\triangle PQR$ and $\triangle STU$ have the same area, $PQ = ST,$ so $UV = ST/2.$

The height of parallelogram $UVRW$ is the same as the height of $\triangle PQR,$ which is twice the height of $\triangle UVW.$  Since the area of $\triangle PQR$ is 1, the height of $\triangle PQR$ is $2/PQ = 2/(2ST) = 1/ST.$  Therefore, the height of parallelogram $UVRW$ is $2/(ST) = 2 \cdot (UV/ST) = 2 \cdot (UV/PQ) = 2 \cdot (UV/2ST) = UV/(ST).$

Therefore, the area of parallelogram $UVRW$ is \[
UV \cdot \frac{UV}{ST} = \frac{UV^2}{ST} = \frac{(ST/2)^2}{ST} = \frac{ST^2}{4ST} = \boxed{\frac{ST}{4}}.
\]

